 |term       = 12th
 |electorate = {{NZ electorate link|City of Dunedin}}
 |party      = Liberal–Labour (New Zealand)
}}
{{NZ parlbox footer}}
In {{NZ election link year|1890}}, Earnshaw contested the {{NZ electorate link|Peninsula}} electorate against the incumbent, [[William Larnach]]. Earnshaw's victory made him a national figure, one of the new breed of working-class MPs.{{sfn|Thomson |1998 |p=144}} Earnshaw represented the Peninsula electorate until the end of the term in 1893, and then the [[Dunedin (New Zealand electorate)|City of Dunedin]] electorate ({{NZ election link year|1893}}–1896) in the [[New Zealand House of Representatives|House of Representatives]].{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=194}} A strong prohibitionist, Earnshaw became one of Sir [[Robert Stout]]'s few consistent supporters in [[New Zealand Parliament|Parliament]] after [[New Zealand general election, 1893|1893]]. This put him off-side with Premier [[Richard Seddon]].

Earnshaw came seventh in the three-member Dunedin electorate in the {{NZ election link|1896}}.<ref>{{cite news |title=Otago |url= http://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/paperspast?a=d&cl=search&d=AS18961223.2.28.16 |accessdate=6 January 2014 |newspaper=[[Auckland Star]] |date=23 December 1896 |volume=XXVII |issue=305 |page=6}}</ref> He came eighth in the three-member {{NZ electorate link|Wellington}} electorate in the {{NZ election link|1899}}.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://atojs.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/atojs?a=d&cl=search&d=AJHR1900-I.2.3.2.54 |title=The General Election, 1899 |date=19 June 1900 |publisher= Appendix to the Journals of the House of Representatives |page=2 |accessdate=12 February 2014 |location=Wellington}}</ref>

Earnshaw was appointed to the [[New Zealand Legislative Council|Legislative Council]] in 1913 and served until his death in 1931.{{sfn|Wilson|1985|p=152}}

==Life outside parliament==
After his 1899 defeat, Earnshaw moved to [[Gillespies Beach]] near [[Fox Glacier]], where he was involved in dredging. He later took employment with the [[Wellington Harbour Board]] prior to his appointment to the Legislative Council.{{sfn|Scholefield|1940|p=225}}

He died on 29 December 1931 at [[Wellington Hospital, New Zealand|Wellington Hospital]] after a short illness. He was survived by his wife and two sons.<ref name="EP obit" /> His wife died in 1947, and both are buried at [[Karori Cemetery]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Details |url= http://wellington.govt.nz/services/community-and-culture/cemeteries/cemeteries-search/details?id=17616&serviceType=Burial |publisher=[[Wellington City Council]] |accessdate=14 February 2014}}</ref>

